CI and CD: Build HelloWorld App and Deploy HelloWorld App

Date: 2026-07-13

Overview

This document describes every step in the CI workflow (`Build HelloWorld App.yml`) and the CD workflow (`cd.yml`) in this repository. It explains triggers, permissions, jobs, step-level details, run_id resolution, manual dispatch usage, and recommended improvements.

CI ‚Äî Build HelloWorld App (Detailed Steps)

1. Triggers
- `push` on branches: `main`, `develop`, `qa`.
- `pull_request` targeting `main`, `develop`, `qa`.
- `workflow_dispatch` with input `branch` (manual run is supported).

2. Permissions
- `id-token: write` ‚Äî enables OIDC token issuance for cloud login actions.
- `contents: read` ‚Äî allows reading repository contents (checkout, download artifacts when needed).
- `actions: read` ‚Äî read access for GitHub Actions metadata.
- `security-events: write` ‚Äî used for security events reporting where applicable.

3. Jobs and steps
- Job: `validate` (Validate (format & restore)) ‚Äî runs on `ubuntu-latest`.
  - `actions/checkout@v4` ‚Äî checks out code.
  - `actions/setup-dotnet@v4` (`dotnet-version: '8.0.x'`) ‚Äî prepares .NET SDK.
  - `dotnet restore src/HelloWorld/HelloWorld.csproj` ‚Äî restore NuGet packages.
  - `dotnet format src/HelloWorld/HelloWorld.csproj` ‚Äî runs formatting check; fails if code is not formatted.
  - Purpose: Fail early for format and dependency problems.

- Job: `build` (Build) ‚Äî runs-on `ubuntu-latest`, `needs: validate`.
  - `actions/checkout@v4`.
  - `actions/setup-dotnet@v4`.
  - `dotnet restore` (again) and `dotnet build src/HelloWorld/HelloWorld.csproj -c Release`.
  - Purpose: Compile and verify the code builds successfully.

- Job: `package` (Package Artifact) ‚Äî runs-on `ubuntu-latest`, `needs: build`, `if: success()`.
  - `actions/checkout@v4` and `actions/setup-dotnet@v4`.
  - `dotnet publish -c Release -o ./artifacts/publish` ‚Äî publish output to folder.
  - `cd artifacts/publish` and `zip -r ../helloworld-artifact.zip .` ‚Äî package published output.
  - `ls -la ./artifacts/helloworld-artifact.zip` ‚Äî validate artifact exists.
  - `actions/upload-artifact@v4` with `name: helloworld-artifact` and `path: ./artifacts/helloworld-artifact.zip` ‚Äî upload artifact into the build run.
  - Purpose: Produce an artifact that can be downloaded by downstream deploy jobs.

- Job: `call-deploy` (Trigger Deploy) ‚Äî `needs: package`, `if: github.event_name == 'push'`.
  - Reuses the CD workflow: `uses: ./.github/workflows/cd.yml` (a reusable workflow call).
  - Passes `with: branch: ${{ github.ref_name }}` and `run_id: ${{ github.run_id }}`.
  - `secrets: inherit` to forward repository secrets to the called workflow.
  - Purpose: Automatically trigger deployment after a successful push-build.

CD ‚Äî Deploy HelloWorld App (Detailed Steps)

1. Entry points
- `workflow_call` ‚Äî allows CI to call CD as a reusable workflow. Inputs required by the call: `branch` and `run_id`.
- `workflow_dispatch` ‚Äî allows manual runs; `branch` input is required. (Optional `run_id` can be passed manually if added to `workflow_dispatch` inputs.)

2. Permissions
- `contents: read` ‚Äî needed to download artifacts and repository contents.
- `id-token: write` ‚Äî for OIDC-based Azure login.
- `actions: read` ‚Äî read actions metadata.

3. Jobs and steps
- Job: `resolve-run-id` (Artifact ID)
  - runs-on: `ubuntu-latest`.
  - Outputs: `run_id` and `branch`.
  - Step: `Set branch value` ‚Äî writes the input `branch` to the job output so downstream jobs can use it.
  - Step: `Get run_id (from input or latest successful build)`
    - If `inputs.run_id` is provided and non-empty, it is used directly.
    - Else the job runs `gh run list` to find the latest successful build for the workflow named `"Build HelloWorld App"` on the requested branch. Command used:
      gh run list --repo ${{ github.repository }} --workflow "Build HelloWorld App" --branch "${{ inputs.branch }}" --status success --limit 1 --json databaseId --jq '.[0].databaseId'
    - The found databaseId is the numeric run id used by `actions/download-artifact`.
    - The resolved `run_id` is written to `$GITHUB_OUTPUT` for downstream jobs.
  - Notes: If `gh run list` returns no results, the shell step fails and the job exits non-zero (this is the error you saw). This typically happens when the workflow name doesn't match or there are no successful runs for the branch.

- Job: `deploy-dev` (Deploy to development environment)
  - `needs: resolve-run-id`.
  - `if: ${{ needs.resolve-run-id.outputs.branch == 'develop' }}` ‚Äî runs only when branch is `develop`.
  - Steps:
    - `actions/checkout@v4` ‚Äî checkout the repo (not strictly required for artifact download but common pattern).
    - `actions/download-artifact@v4` with:
      - `name: helloworld-artifact`
      - `path: ./publish`
      - `repository: ${{ github.repository }}`
      - `run-id: ${{ needs.resolve-run-id.outputs.run_id }}`
      - `github-token: ${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }}`
      - This downloads the artifact zip from the specified build run into `./publish`.
    - `azure/login@v2` with dev-specific service principal secrets.
    - `Azure/functions-action@v1` to deploy `./publish/helloworld-artifact.zip` to the dev Function App.
    - Logout step to `az logout` with `if: always()`.

- Job: `deploy-qa` ‚Äî same as deploy-dev but gated by `if: branch == 'qa'` and using QA secrets. Declares `environment: qa`.

- Job: `deploy-prod` ‚Äî same pattern, gated by `if: branch == 'main'` and using Production secrets; `environment: Production`.

How artifacts are located and downloaded
- `actions/upload-artifact@v4` attaches `helloworld-artifact` to the Build run.
- CD uses either a provided `run_id` (from CI or from manual input) or resolves the latest successful build run id for the `Build HelloWorld App` workflow on the specified `branch` using `gh run list`.
- `actions/download-artifact@v4` with `run-id: <id>` downloads the artifact from that specific run.

Manual deployment usage (examples)
- Deploy latest `develop` build (no explicit run_id):
  - Actions ‚Üí `Deploy HelloWorld App` ‚Üí Run workflow
  - Set `branch` = `develop` and run. CD resolves latest successful `Build HelloWorld App` run on `develop` and deploys it.

- Deploy a specific `qa` build by run id:
  - Find run id: Actions ‚Üí `Build HelloWorld App` ‚Üí open the desired run ‚Üí copy the run databaseId (or run number depending on your tracking).
  - Actions ‚Üí `Deploy HelloWorld App` ‚Üí Run workflow
  - Set `branch` = `qa` and `run_id` = `<value>` (if `run_id` is added to `workflow_dispatch`) and run.

Common failure scenarios and troubleshooting
- Error: "could not find any workflows named Build HelloWorld App"
  - Cause: `gh run list` uses the workflow `name` field. If the `name:` doesn't match, `gh` finds nothing.
  - Fix: ensure `Build HelloWorld App.yml` defines `name: Build HelloWorld App` OR change the `--workflow` argument to match the actual workflow name.

- Error: "No successful build runs found"
  - Cause: There are no successful `Build HelloWorld App` runs on the requested branch.
  - Fix: run the build on that branch (push or `workflow_dispatch`) and retry deploy.

- Error: `actions/download-artifact` fails with 404 or not found
  - Cause: invalid `run-id` or artifact not present on that run.
  - Fix: verify the run-id and confirm `helloworld-artifact` exists on the build run.

Recommended improvements (optional)
- Add `run_id` as an optional `workflow_dispatch` input in `cd.yml` so manual runs can target a specific run.
- After resolving `LATEST_RUN_ID`, add a defensive check and a clearer error message:
  - if empty then echo a user-friendly message and `exit 1`.
- Add an explicit log step showing resolved `run_id` before download for traceability.
- Ensure the `gh` CLI is available and pinned, or install it explicitly in the runner for consistency.
- Consider `concurrency` in `cd.yml` to avoid concurrent deploys for the same branch:
  concurrency:
    group: cd-${{ inputs.branch }}
    cancel-in-progress: true

Notes about tokens and `gh`
- The `gh run list` command in `cd.yml` uses `GH_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }}`. The `gh` CLI picks it up from the environment.
- Ensure `secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN` has read access to actions/runs. The default token in workflow context normally works for these operations.

Validation checklist before manual deploy
- [ ] Confirm at least one successful `Build HelloWorld App` run exists for the `branch` you want to deploy.
- [ ] If deploying a specific run, copy the exact run id and pass as `run_id`.
- [ ] Confirm secrets for the target environment (DEV/QA/PROD) are configured in repository settings.

